title: Indexing behavior + versioning
body:
# Motivation

Currently the behavior of the ANN functionality is not formally defined when you create a new version via append/overwrite. This can result in surprise and wrong answers.

# Desired behavior

1. `lance.write_dataset(..., mode='overwrite')` should invalidate the index so it is not visible by the new version Manifest.
2. `lance.write_dataset(..., mode='append')` should preserve the index.
3. When performing ANN search on a lance dataset, lance should also search through new vectors since index creation using flat and the result should be combined with the indexed ANN search.

title: Support version tagging
body:
Git-like version tags make it easier to manage lots of versions and quickly know which versions are released for example.

Version tags should be written to the version Manifest (protos: https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/protos/format.proto#L74, rust: https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/format/manifest.rs#L55)

## Write
1. Manifest file is written [here](https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/dataset.rs#L271) when writing a dataset.
2. The version tag should be passed down from [python](https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/python/python/lance/dataset.py#L496) -> [pyo3](https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/python/src/dataset.rs#L242) -> core lance (see step 1).
3. Currently only WriteParams are passed down to core lance. The API should distinguish writeparams and metadata so it's probably best to create a new struct that can be extended to hold (1) tags, (2) schema metadata, and (3) version-specific metadata

## Read
The tag needs to be added to the PyDict in the pyo3 code: https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/python/src/dataset.rs#L183

## Checkout

On the python side, add a convenience feature to checkout a tag instead of a specific version number

title: Support for Null array
body:
# Problem Statement

Support `null` type array.

https://arrow.apache.org/docs/python/generated/pyarrow.null.html#pyarrow.null


## Write

Null arrays are special. A Null type field should be written into the schema but no data should be persisted to disk.

For `write_array` (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/io/writer.rs#L155), add a special case for null field type and don't actually write the array.

## Read
Instead, the Array should be created on the fly when read. Add a special case to (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/io/reader.rs#L295) and create a null array on the fly

title: python api lists the same timestamp for all versions of a dataset
body:
Hi - I ran into this issue while trying to make a PR for #506 .

The `versions` method on a Lance dataset returns the same timestamp for all the versions, despite them being written with >1s intervals. 

Repro:

```py
import shutil
import time
from datetime import datetime

import lance
import pandas as pd
import pyarrow as pa

# create a new dataset and append to it two more times
base_dir = "test_asof"
shutil.rmtree(base_dir, ignore_errors=True)

table = pa.Table.from_pydict({"colA": [1, 2, 3], "colB": [4, 5, 6]})
ds = lance.write_dataset(table, base_dir, mode="create")

time.sleep(1)
ds = lance.write_dataset(table, base_dir, mode="append")

time.sleep(1)
ds = lance.write_dataset(table, base_dir, mode="append")

print(ds.versions())
```

This produces the following, which is the `datetime.now()` value for all versions. 
```txt
[{'version': 1,
  'timestamp': datetime.datetime(2023, 2, 14, 19, 56, 29),
  'metadata': {}},
 {'version': 3,
  'timestamp': datetime.datetime(2023, 2, 14, 19, 56, 29),
  'metadata': {}},
 {'version': 2,
  'timestamp': datetime.datetime(2023, 2, 14, 19, 56, 29),
  'metadata': {}}]
```

Looking at the modified times for the 3 different manifests confirms there is no overwriting, the python API is seemingly reading it incorrectly. 

```py
import os

for i in (1, 2, 3):
    print(datetime.fromtimestamp(os.path.getmtime(f"test_asof/_versions/{i}.manifest")))
```

```txt
2023-02-14 19:50:54.074557
2023-02-14 19:50:55.097677
2023-02-14 19:50:56.111796
```

title: Support for Arrow Duration
body:
Arrow has a duration type: https://arrow.apache.org/docs/cpp/api/datatype.html#_CPPv48durationN8TimeUnit4typeE

Support for this should be added to Lance. 

## Type mapping
1. Add type mapping from Arrow -> Lance (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/datatypes.rs#L61)
2. Add type mapping from Lance -> Arrow (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/datatypes.rs#L124)
3. Add type round trip tests (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/datatypes.rs#L761). Make sure to test the TimeUnit parametrization.

## Encoding / decoding
1. A duration is fixed width integer, so just use the plain encoder/decoder (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/rust/src/encodings/plain.rs).
2. First add a read-write unit test and verify that it fails the roundtrip.
3. Add duration type to is_fixed_stride (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/51afc0052d73ed0e537ef6b2fdf3f6059d0b5548/rust/src/arrow.rs#L77) so lance knows to use the plain encoding

## Reference

See https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/pull/584 for similar implementation for decimal 128 and 256 types

title: overwrite and append mode behavior
body:
Transcribing/Paraphrasing feedback from a separate venue.

When using `lance.write_dataset` it's not obvious whether the dataset already exists. The current semantics are:

```
create - if it exists then raises an error, otherwise writes new dataset folder
overwrite - if it exists then it writes a new version, otherwise raises error
append - if it exists then it writes a new version, otherwise raises error
```

A user reported that "if the file does not exist, I would expect the function to create it, but instead, I see an error that the manifest doesn't exist".

An additional suggestion was "For append, I'd say issue a warning then make a new one"

title: Index creation time can be slow when there's no SIMD alignment
body:
In `LanceDataset.create_index`,  if (num_partitions / num_subvectors) % 8 != 0  then there is no SIMD alignment so index creation speed becomes interminably slow.

The user does not know to do that or have information to debug this when it's the case. We should:

1. If the user does not specify `num_sub_vectors`, automatically calculate an optimal one that guarantees SIMD alignment. If the number of dimensions is not a multiple of 8, then print a warning message.
2. If the user does specify `num_sub_vectors`, check if the quotient above is a multiple of 8 and print warning message as necessary.

title: Expose DataFragment via Python SDK
body:
# Problem Statement

By exposing the layout of the dataset, it could allow several distributed computing/training frameworks to load the Lance dataset in parallel as a stop-gap measure. 

For example, an envisioned workaround in PySpark to load Lance distributedly (without building the Spark DataSource first) could be  

```python

import lance
import pyspark

fragments = lance.dataset("uri").fragments()
fragments_df = pyspark.createDataFrame({"fragments": fragments}).repartition(num_of_executors)

fragmetns_df.rdd.flatmap(read_fragment).toDF(schema)
```

And a PyTorch distributed dataset could similar to our old PyTorch reader.

https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/branch-0.2/python/lance/pytorch/data.py#L155-L164

2. Instead of returning a PyDict for each version (https://github.com/eto-ai/lance/blob/main/python/src/dataset.rs#L182), create a pyo3 struct Version that is exposed to python. This struct should have a function to read the aux data and cache it in memory.
